
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `eog` (Eye of GNOME) yek barnamaye sade baraye didan tasvir-ha dar Linux ast. Ba in dastoor mitoonid tasvir-ha ro baz konid, zoom konid, va tasvir-ha ro moroor konid.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `eog file.jpg`        --> 🖼️ Baz kardane yek tasvir khass.
    🔹 `eog pooshe/`          --> 📂 Baz kardane hameye tasvir-ha dar yek pooshe.
    🔹 `eog -f`            --> 🖥️ Baz kardane EOG dar halat tamame sahne (fullscreen).
    🔹 `eog --slide-show`   --> 🎞️ Baz kardane tasvir-ha be soorate slide show.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ eog aks.png

    🔹 Baz kardane tasvir "aks.png".

    $ eog /home/user/tasvir-ha/

    🔹 Baz kardane hameye tasvir-ha dar pooshe "tasvir-ha".

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ eog -f aks.jpg

    🔹 Tasvir "aks.jpg" dar halat tamame sahne baz mishe, ke behtarin halat baraye didane aks be soorate bozorg ast.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `eog` (Eye of GNOME) command is a simple image viewer for Linux.  You can use this command to open, zoom, and browse images.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `eog file.jpg`        --> 🖼️ Opens a specific image.
    🔹 `eog directory/`    --> 📂 Opens all images in a directory.
    🔹 `eog -f`            --> 🖥️ Opens EOG in fullscreen mode.
    🔹 `eog --slide-show`   --> 🎞️ Opens images in a slideshow.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ eog image.png

    🔹 Opens the image "image.png".

    $ eog /home/user/images/

    🔹 Opens all images in the "images" directory.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ eog -f image.jpg

    🔹 Opens the "image.jpg" in fullscreen mode, which is ideal for viewing images in a larger format.
